msDesc.head: Composite manuscript, including Gospel of Mark (with gloss) with legal and other texts

supportDesc.condition: Most of folio 14 excised. Folio 1 is darkened and dirty, and ff. 142-172 are stained, increasingly towards the rear of the volume, suggesting that the manuscript(s) were without bindings for some time.

history.acquisition: Given to Pembroke College, Cambridge Pembroke College in 1599 by William Smart (d. 1599) Smart, William, portreeve of Ipswich, -1599 . Wren List 34 James, Ecloga, no. 251

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on the description provided by Rodney M. Thomson, A descriptive catalogue of the medieval manuscripts at Pembroke College, Cambridge (2022) (used here by kind permission of the author).

availability.p: Researchers should note that Pembroke College's western European medieval manuscripts are housed at Cambridge University Library (CUL). Scholars who wish to consult Pembroke College manuscripts should contact the Manuscripts Reading Room at CUL to arrange their visit; all CUL admissions procedures will apply. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library. For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.

msItem.title: Gospel of Mark
msItem.incipit: 2r: Inicium ewangelii ihesu christi filii dei sicut scriptum est in ysaia propheta

seg.seg: Text: Ruled in crayon, 17 lines. Written above top line in long lines, on alternate lines and in larger script than the gloss, in the middle of the page at a consistent width of 85 mm.

Gloss: Ruled in crayon for 43-47 lines of gloss, not all occupied, written above top line in two columns, one either side of the text and occasionally overlapping with it at the foot. The left-hand column 50 mm; the right-hand column 55 mm. The columns are ruled independently of the text and of each other. The gloss occurs mainly in short blocks, much or all of the column being left blank.

handNote.p:
Written by two proficient scribes in English protogothic bookhand:
1. ff. 1r-64v for the text, and ff. 1r-61r for the gloss. Hand also found in Dublin, Trinity College, MS 492, another Bury manuscript.
2. ff. 65r-66r for the text, and 61v-66r for the gloss.

decoNote.p: Anthropomorphic initial M, outlined in the same ink as that used for the text and tinted red and green, in the form of a seated monk holding red and green dragons with holy wafers in their mouths (f. 1r).
Zoomorphic initial I, outlined in the same ink as that used for the text and tinted yellow, in the form of a dragon with a holy wafer in its mouth (f. 2r).
Titulus in red and green capitals (f. 1r).
Red and pale green initials in the text.
Blocks of gloss open with decorative paraphs in the same ink as that used for the text.

origin.p: Written at the Abbey of Bury St Edmunds Abbey of Bury St. Edmunds (perhaps CBMLC 4, B13.229).

provenance.p: An ex libris by the early 13th-century 'ex libris hand' of the Abbey of Bury St Edmunds Abbey of Bury St. Edmunds (f. 1r).
Ex libris, pressmark (B.101) and title, written by the hand of Henry Kirkestede (c. 1314-c. 1379) Kirkestede, Henry, approximately 1314-approximately 1378 (f. 1r).

msItem.note: Covers Gratian Gratian, active 12th century , Decretum D.1-C.24 q.3.

msItem.title: Casus super Codicem IV-VII
msItem.incipit: 76r: potior est in iure tamen fallit hic... (Diuersis temporibus) sit generaliter quicquid priorem tempore
msItem.note: The text breaks off at f. 79r (donauit mihi predia quas an eius). Folios 80r-81v were filled by a later, cursive hand (In titulo de accionibus post primam diuisionem primo tractat dominus imperator de accionibus in rem...), breaking off with a note on Rescripta (end of quire).
The main scribe resumes on f. 82r, (Ex caucione etc. duobus modis potest poni tantus primo sic... inpendisse an expense ueniant).
Most of f. 87v is blank, and the bottom third of the second column of f. 100v, and f. 109r.
Folio 109 blank, with a few pencil notes on the verso.
